2) If you did get married were the witnesses only from your side and did the person who the Wali delegated permission to someone who was known more to you than the wali?
3) Furthermore, if you did get married did you ask the woman who you married to hide the marriage from her own father and family? 

If you did get married its a pity you have become like many brothers out there and have manipulated the rules of Islam without any thought about the intention behind the rulings to uphold good manners and society.

If you have daughters and someone was to marry her in this way would this be acceptable? Would you start berating the individual with Islamic edicts or worse? 

It would be good for the youth if you speak out about this situation to avoid our children from following in your footsteps and ending up having secret marriages "to make it halal" with girls at college or university without revealing this to their parents or anyone - 

For the good of our next generation you need to clarify the situation - if there is a wakeel he should be sincere in protecting her rights and adhering to what he knows the wakeel would have wanted - each role during the marriage has responsibilities which needs to be fulfilled. Also any witnesses of a marriage should come forward to testify the marriage occurred otherwise what is the point of the witnesses - in summary brother the community and our youth need you to accept any fault, if there is any, and be honest about this situation and provide a lesson for those who follow you. Lets not stain the Dawah and provide transparency and honesty - marriage or divorce is not a secret affair rather it should be announced to ensure it is widely known and misunderstandings don't occur.
